{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 5. Competitive Narrative\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.1 vs.\u160 ?Uniswap\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Uniswap pioneered AMMs. We respect that. But continuous execution creates MEV \u8212- that\u8217's not a bug, it\u8217's the architecture. Batch auctions are the next evolution. Same liquidity depth, zero extraction.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.2 vs.\u160 ?CoW Swap\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"CoW Swap uses solvers and coincidence of wants. Good idea, complex execution. We use commit-reveal batch auctions \u8212- simpler mechanism, same MEV protection, plus omnichain via LayerZero.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.3 vs.\u160 ?1inch / Jupiter\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Aggregators route through extractive pools. They optimize the route, not the mechanism. We fix the mechanism. When every pool is fair, you don\u8217't need to route around unfairness.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
